<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-881-866  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 881 866.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Lasers andamp; Optronics  Sept 1989 v8 n9 p45(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Red-emitting diode lasers move toward mainstream. (technical)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Cunningham, Richard.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The advent of commercially available red diode lasers that emit inthe 780-nanometer and shorter wavelengths is expected to impactseriously those markets currently dominated by helium-neon gaslasers.andP;  The red diode lasers typically consist of active andconfinement layers of AlGaInP on a GaAs substrate, with productionversions typically emitting in the 670-nanometer region.andO;Laboratory versions offer wavelengths as short as 625 nanometers.andO;Likely applications for the new generation of red diode lasersinclude: laser printers, bar-code readers, optical memorysubsystems, pointers and instrumentation.andP;  Advantages of thetechnology for each application are briefly described.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     TrendsDiodesLasersTechnologyNew TechniqueResearch and DevelopmentGallium Arsenide Semiconductors.andO;Feature:   illustrationchartgraph.andO;Caption:   Structure of AlGaInP visible semiconductor laser. (chart)Far-field emission pattern of the Toshiba TOLD9200 670-nm diodelaser. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>